<methodology slug="blurred-roles-team-evolution">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>product</group>
    <domain>product-manager</domain>
    <summary>Product teams as overlapping Venn diagrams with PM fluency in design, data, and AI. DRI per overlap zone, quarterly audits, and human convergence replace handoff structures.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>team-structure</tag>
      <tag>pm-skills</tag>
      <tag>cross-functional</tag>
      <tag>ai-era</tag>
      <tag>role-evolution</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>advanced</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Blurred Roles and Team Evolution</title>
    <summary>Modern product teams operate as overlapping Venn diagrams rather than relay-race handoffs. PMs are expected to speak design fluently, understand data deeply, know how AI models work, and have a credible view on distribution and pricing. Each PM-vs-X overlap zone (PM/design, PM/growth, PM/engineer, PM/data) must have exactly one human DRI; agents fill the zone, the PM converges decisions.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>AI-augmented engineers ship faster, shifting the bottleneck to discovery, evals, and prioritization — all PM work. Andrew Ng observed a 2:1 PM:Engineer ratio emerging in AI-era teams. Traditional handoff-based structures create delays and gaps between handoffs where churn lives. The Venn model is the operating model for 2026, not a future aspiration.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Redefining the PM job description in an AI-augmented team where subagents handle research, prototyping, and copy PMs used to broker.</item>
        <item>Inverting the PM:Engineer ratio when engineers ship via AI coding tools.</item>
        <item>Drafting hiring scorecards for AI-era PMs: SQL fluency, eval authoring, design literacy.</item>
        <item>Resolving PM-vs-X identity collisions that surface when each role gains agent leverage.</item>
        <item>Quarterly audit of current PM responsibilities vs. the Venn target.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Solopreneur/founder team — you are the Venn; use product-operations variant instead.</item>
        <item>Regulated product surfaces (HIPAA, SOX, PCI) where PM/QA/compliance separation is auditable.</item>
        <item>Performance reviews or leveling — the Venn model is an operating-model lens, not a competency rubric.</item>
        <item>Teams under heavy delivery pressure mid-sprint — role restructuring is a quiet-quarter activity.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="traditional-vs-ai-era-pm-skillset">
      <p>Traditional PM skills: write specs, own roadmap, manage stakeholders, prioritize features. AI-era PM additionally requires: speak design fluently, understand data deeply (write SQL), know how models work, have a credible view on distribution and pricing strategy.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Write every PM job description as "primary lens (product strategy) + 3 fluencies (data, design, AI) + 1 specialist depth + explicit non-goals" rather than a flat skill list.</statement>
        <rationale>A flat skill list produces shallow generalism and fails to encode where the PM does NOT own depth; the T-shape with explicit non-goals prevents PM burnout from absorbing every discipline.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="team-ratio-evolution">
      <p>Traditional ratio: 1 PM to 4-8 engineers. AI-era ratio: 2 PMs to 1 engineer (Andrew Ng observation). This holds only when the engineer is heavily AI-augmented — track agent-assisted velocity separately before changing the ratio. The bottleneck shifts to discovery, evals, and prioritization — all PM work.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Treat the 2:1 PM:Engineer ratio as a hypothesis per team, not an industry benchmark; validate against actual agent-assisted engineering throughput before any hiring decision.</statement>
        <rationale>The ratio was one observation from one operator; applying it without measuring current agent-assisted velocity risks over-hiring PMs and under-building the product.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="cross-functional-expectations">
      <p>Role expectations in AI-era teams: PM — speak design, understand data, know AI basics; Designer — understand constraints, track activation metrics, own one funnel; Engineer — join discovery, talk to customers; Data — participate in product decisions, not just supply numbers.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Pair every "PM speaks design" expectation with a designer-side blurring expectation; one-sided blurring breeds resentment and burns out the PM.</statement>
        <rationale>The Venn model describes mutual overlap, not PM absorption of all disciplines; unilateral blurring turns the PM into a permanent integrator with no leverage.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="specialist-retention">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Full blurring expectations on deep domains (security, accessibility, ML eval, monetization) with no specialist backstop.</description>
        <reason>Full blurring is an anti-pattern in deep domains; keep one depth specialist PM per critical surface as the audit backstop — the Venn model does not mean every PM must be equally broad in every area.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Using the Venn model as a hiring filter that shuts out specialists (deep researcher, deep platform PM, deep growth PM).</description>
        <reason>Skill-blurring expectations in JDs covertly reject candidates the team actually needs; label specialist roles explicitly rather than requiring generalism that doesn't exist in the market.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="dri-assignment-per-overlap-zone">
      <rule>
        <statement>Name exactly one human PM DRI for each overlap zone (PM/design, PM/growth, PM/engineer, PM/data, PM/eval); agents fill the zone but only the PM closes decisions.</statement>
        <rationale>A zone without a DRI becomes a place where decisions stall instead of accelerate — the Venn overlap is only productive when the convergence point is a named human with decision authority.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Document the DRI assignment in the PM job description, not in tribal knowledge; it must survive PM turnover.</statement>
        <rationale>Undocumented DRI assignments disappear when the PM leaves; the next PM inherits ambiguity and re-creates the handoff gaps the Venn model was designed to eliminate.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="agent-role-constraints">
      <rule>
        <statement>Constrain agent personas via tool allow-lists: faion-mvp-scope-analyzer-agent must not have Edit permissions on source files; PM-vs-engineer overlap must not collapse at the file level.</statement>
        <rationale>An agent given the PM JD plus repo access will silently rewrite code in the PM-vs-engineer overlap zone; tool allow-lists are the only reliable constraint, not prompt instructions.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Use brainstorm to fan out persona-flavored agents (PM-agent, designer-agent, growth-agent, eng-agent) on the same problem in parallel, then converge in a PM-DRI session.</statement>
        <rationale>Parallel role-persona agents produce contradictions; without a human PM-DRI to converge, the PRD ships the loudest agent's recommendation — the diverge-converge structure forces explicit resolution.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent-driven PM evaluations rating PM data fluency from PRDs used as performance inputs.</description>
        <reason>LLMs are biased toward verbose writers and score calibration against PRD length, not insight; use as a discussion seed only, never as a performance or leveling input.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="quarterly-scope-audit">
      <rule>
        <statement>Re-audit PM scope quarterly with improver; blurred PM roles drift back to delivery-brokering under deadline pressure.</statement>
        <rationale>Scope drift is invisible without measurement; the quarterly audit forces the conversation about where the PM actually spent time vs. the Venn target, using commit-author and ticket-assignee data as ground truth.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Use commit-author and Linear/Jira-assignee distribution as the truth signal for current PM scope; self-reported scope in surveys is systematically wrong by approximately 30%.</statement>
        <rationale>PMs systematically under-report time spent on delivery brokering and over-report time on discovery; objective data from git and trackers corrects this bias.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="human-in-the-loop-checkpoints">
      <list>
        <item>PM-DRI assignment per overlap zone — before any agent pair runs on a shared problem.</item>
        <item>Approval of any PM JD rewrite generated by an agent.</item>
        <item>Explicit sign-off on PM:Engineer ratio change before any hiring action.</item>
        <item>PM review of every eval set drafted by an agent before it enters a test suite.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>For each PM-vs-X overlap zone (PM/design, PM/growth, PM/engineer, PM/data, PM/eval), name a single human DRI and a Claude subagent that runs the parallel disciplinary lens. The PM owns the converged decision artifact (PRD, eval set, growth brief). Use brainstorm to fan out persona-flavored agents (PM-agent, designer-agent, growth-agent, eng-agent) on the same problem, then converge in a PM-DRI session. For role-evolution audits, run improver to compare current responsibilities against a target Venn and emit SDD tasks. Never let an agent persona own a decision in an overlap zone — agents propose, the human PM decides.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="recommended-subagents">
      <list>
        <item>faion-mlp-agent — PM-owned MVP/MLP shaping; absorbs the "PM speaks design + tracks metrics + understands data" expectation by running its 5 modes (analyze, find-gaps, propose, update, plan) and emitting structured artifacts the PM converges on.</item>
        <item>faion-mvp-scope-analyzer-agent — PM-owned competitor + scope analysis; replaces the "PM goes asks the analyst" handoff that the methodology says is dead.</item>
        <item>brainstorm — diverge across role personas (PM, designer, growth, eng, data) on a shared problem; the PM is the converger, not a participant in diverge.</item>
        <item>improver — quarterly audit of "what is the PM currently doing vs. the Venn target"; emits gap list and SDD tasks.</item>
        <item>faion-sdd-executor-agent — execute the PM-restructure tasks (rewriting JDs, RACI updates, skill plans, agent-allowlist edits) under quality gates.</item>
        <item>researcher (knowledge skill) — pull external benchmarks (PM:Eng ratios, PM JDs at AI-native companies) when the PM is calibrating their own role.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="prompt-pattern-disciplinary-lens">
      <p>You are ROLE-agent (designer | growth | eng | data) reviewing PRD draft at PATH. The PM is the DRI. Produce only your discipline's lens: risks, missing inputs, conflicts with your role's metrics. Do NOT synthesize across roles; do NOT propose final scope. Output JSON with keys: risks[], missing_inputs[], conflicts[], suggested_questions[].</p>
    </section>
    <section name="prompt-pattern-pm-convergence">
      <p>You are PM-DRI for product P. Read the parallel disciplinary lenses in DIR/lens-*.json (designer, growth, eng, data). Converge into a single PRD: explicit decisions per overlap zone, explicit "deferred to specialist" markers where you choose not to absorb the discipline. Emit PRD.md plus decisions.csv (zone, decision, rationale, owner).</p>
    </section>
    <section name="cli-tools">
      <list>
        <item>gh + CODEOWNERS — Where the PM-vs-eng line currently sits in code; PRs touching files PM owns are the overlap signal. https://cli.github.com</item>
        <item>linear MCP / linear-cli — Pull PM ticket distribution: ratio of discovery vs. delivery vs. handoff tickets per PM. https://github.com/evangelion-ui/linear-cli</item>
        <item>dbt / duckdb — The "PM understands data deeply" expectation operationalized: PM writes SQL or dbt models against product analytics. https://docs.getdbt.com ; https://duckdb.org</item>
        <item>figma MCP — "PM speaks design fluently" — read Figma comments and frames programmatically; agent generates PM annotations. https://github.com/GLips/Figma-Context-MCP</item>
        <item>posthog / amplitude CLI / API — PM-owned funnel/retention queries the PM used to ask the analyst for. https://posthog.com/docs/api ; https://developers.amplitude.com</item>
        <item>claude (Claude Code) — Drive the persona-lens agents non-interactively for batch role audits and JD rewrites. https://docs.anthropic.com/en/docs/claude-code</item>
        <item>notion MCP — Sync PM JD, RACI per overlap zone, growth plan into the team wiki. https://github.com/makenotion/notion-mcp-server</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="services-and-apps">
      <list>
        <item>Linear (SaaS) — Yes (REST + MCP). Best signal for PM ticket-type distribution; query labels/assignees to derive current PM scope.</item>
        <item>Productboard (SaaS) — Partial (REST). PM-owned product+metric overlap; useful when PM absorbs analyst role.</item>
        <item>PostHog / Amplitude / Mixpanel (SaaS / OSS for PostHog) — Yes (REST). Direct PM access kills the "PM asks analyst" handoff; agents draft funnels for PM review.</item>
        <item>Figma (SaaS) — Yes (REST + MCP). PM-vs-designer overlap; agents read Figma comments and surface PM action items.</item>
        <item>Maze / UserTesting (SaaS) — Partial (REST). PM-owned discovery; agents schedule, transcript, and synthesize tests.</item>
        <item>Reforge / Lenny's "PM AI" (SaaS) — No. Curriculum for the new PM skillset; agent role is summarize + map to internal gaps.</item>
        <item>Eval platforms — Braintrust, Langfuse, Humanloop (SaaS). Yes (REST/SDK). "PM authors evals" expectation made operational; agents draft eval sets, PM approves.</item>
        <item>Lattice / 15Five (SaaS) — Partial (REST, gated). Skill-growth tracking for the PM's T-shape; writes usually need human approval.</item>
        <item>GitHub Projects (SaaS) — Yes (gh + GraphQL). Free Linear substitute; CODEOWNERS file is the most concrete PM-vs-eng boundary.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="best-practices">
      <list>
        <item>Make every PM-vs-X overlap zone have exactly one PM DRI; agents fill the zone, but only the human PM closes decisions. Document this in the PM JD, not in tribal knowledge.</item>
        <item>Pair every "PM speaks design" expectation with a designer-side blurring ("designer tracks activation metrics, owns one funnel"). One-sided blurring breeds resentment and burns out the PM.</item>
        <item>When inverting the PM:Engineer ratio, only hire/grow PMs who can write SQL, author evals, and read a model card — otherwise the ratio just creates more meetings and slower decisions.</item>
        <item>Write the PM JD as "primary lens (product strategy) + 3 fluencies (data, design, AI) + 1 specialist depth (e.g., growth or platform)" rather than a flat skill list. Forces explicit T-shape and prevents shallow generalism.</item>
        <item>Use commit-author + Linear-assignee distribution as the truth signal for current PM scope. Self-reported PM scope in surveys is systematically wrong by approximately 30%; agents that audit from prose JDs replicate that error.</item>
        <item>Keep one "depth specialist" PM per critical surface (security, accessibility, ML eval, monetization). Full-blurring is an anti-pattern in deep domains; the specialist is the audit backstop.</item>
        <item>Re-audit PM scope quarterly with improver. Blurred PM roles drift back to delivery-brokering under deadline pressure; the audit is the forcing function.</item>
        <item>Distinguish "PM absorbs the discipline" (PM does it themselves with agents) from "PM gains fluency" (PM can review what an agent or specialist produced). Conflating them kills PMs.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="ai-agent-gotchas">
      <list>
        <item>Parallel role-persona agents on the same PRD produce contradictions; without a human PM-DRI to converge, the PRD ships the loudest agent's recommendation. Always attach a converge step owned by the PM.</item>
        <item>An agent given the PM JD plus repo access will silently rewrite code (PM-vs-engineer overlap collapses). Constrain via tool allow-lists per persona — faion-mvp-scope-analyzer-agent should not have Edit on source files.</item>
        <item>Agent-driven PM evaluations ("rate this PM's data fluency from their PRDs") are noisy and biased toward verbose writers. Use as a discussion seed, never as a performance input.</item>
        <item>The "2 PMs : 1 Engineer" inversion holds only when the engineer is heavily AI-augmented. If you measure on baseline engineering throughput, you'll over-hire PMs and under-build. Track agent-assisted velocity separately before changing the ratio.</item>
        <item>Cross-role agent handoffs leak proprietary context (the data-agent surfaces customer PII into a designer-agent prompt). Run a password-scrubber-agent style filter on inter-agent handoffs that involve PM-owned customer data.</item>
        <item>Agents asked to "redefine the PM role" without constraints will produce maximalist JDs that no human can actually fill. Constrain prompts: "primary lens + max 3 fluencies + 1 specialist depth + explicit non-goals".</item>
        <item>Human-in-the-loop checkpoints: (a) PM-DRI assignment per overlap zone, (b) approval of any PM JD rewrite generated by an agent, (c) explicit sign-off on the PM:Engineer ratio change before any hiring action, (d) PM review of every eval set drafted by an agent.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="methodology-limitations">
      <p>Methodology source content is one page (skill table + Andrew Ng quote + Venn metaphor). It describes a target state, not a transition path — agents will hallucinate process if you ask "implement the methodology".</p>
      <p>"PM speaks design / understands data / knows AI basics" is a one-sided expectation list. Without the matching designer/data/eng-side blurring, the PM becomes a permanent integrator and burns out.</p>
      <p>The 2:1 PM:Engineer ratio is one observation from one operator; treat as a hypothesis per team, not a benchmark. Agents will cite it as if it's industry data — it isn't.</p>
      <p>Blurring without a "decision DRI per overlap zone" creates accountability vacuum: the PM-vs-designer overlap becomes a place where decisions stall instead of accelerate.</p>
      <p>Skill-blurring expectations become covert hiring filters that shut out specialists (deep researcher, deep platform PM, deep growth PM); agents trained on these JDs will reject candidates the team actually needs.</p>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/pm-scope-audit.sh" purpose="Emit PM ticket-type distribution from Linear (discovery vs. delivery vs. handoff)"/>
    </templates>
    <see-also>
      <link href="https://www.svpg.com/">Silicon Valley Product Group, "The Product Operating Model"</link>
      <link href="https://docs.anthropic.com/en/docs/claude-code/sub-agents">Anthropic, Claude Code subagents docs</link>
    </see-also>
  </content>
</methodology>
